The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, February 16, 2004 				 Reliance taps firms for high-speed data service
 M. RAJENDRAN																								New Delhi, Feb. 15: Reliance Infocomm has decided to turn aggressive with its plans to offer high-speed data services to its subscribers. It aims to target large companies and small and medium enterprises.																								As part of its strategy, the company will role out its code division multiple accesss (CDMA) latest product  CDMA2000-1X EVDO  here. 																								The product is already a big hit in the US, South Korea, Japan, China and Brazil. The companys focused target customers  business users  would then be able to get high-speed access to applications like corporate virtual private network, e-mail and calendaring.																								CDMA2000-1X EVDO (evolution data optimised) offers a 2.4-mega bit per second peak data rate in 1.25 megahertz carrier shared among users. This means that use of this technology will not need a higher spectrum. It aims to fulfil personal needs of a variety of users and expand the operators customer base.																								According to Qualcomm, the founder of CDMA technology, 1x-EVDOs fast wire line equivalent experience coupled with rich applications and services are easily accessible on a variety of devices running internet protocol (IP)-based operating systems like Windows, Pocket PC and Macintosh, and bring personalised broadband access to all users. The low-cost advantage of 1x-EVDO allows operators to offer multiple tariff options to meet the needs of their various customer segments.																								We feel that this is an exciting time for broadband-based services. Reliance Infocomm is ready with the latest in broadband and can offer our customers a variety of services like video streaming, video clips, realtime 3D games at a higher speed with more clarity, said Sandeep Sibal, technology adviser to Mukesh Ambani, chairman of Reliance Infocomm.																								The always-on experience, ubiquitous coverage and seamless roaming are key drivers to the adoption of wireless data by various customer segments that Reliance Infocomm plans to leverage, said Sibal. 																								Business customers will soon demand corporate virtual private network and e-mail. The aim is to improve productivity, mobility and work experience. Mobile office, field sales, field service and fleet management are a few of the applications that can be offered, he added.																								According to an analyst in PricewaterhouseCoopers, the wireless broadband will get an impetus in India if attractively priced and offers personalised access to novel, entertaining as well as utilitarian services. 
